  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHADOWKNIGHT</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>REMEMBER WHO YOU ARE...</font> - <small>Feffvolf, Innoruuk</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><P>Alright, I am in Iksar Shadowknight and I've been in this business for a while.  I've read a few of these strageties and I must disagree with alot of them.  Remember you are a Shadowknight, if you wanted to be all melee you should have been a warrior and I apologize that you wasted your time, but then again you are a Shadowknight and not a Necromancer, again I apologize if you wanted to be Mr. or Mrs. Spells.  The beauty of the shadowknight is that your god has given you the gift of both magic and might, the trick to being successful is to combine the two to form an awesome stragety. And no, you are not a necromancer who failed necromancer school! I killed the last blacked robe dark elf who said that.  Just tell them they are Shadowknights who had no life and read books all their life. <br><br>

First of all, the pet situation.  I've seen alot of people who say your pet is useless and not worth the mana it takes to summon him, I am going to highly disagree with these statement.  Your pet will not be as good as you or any of the people you group with if you choose to group however he is a great ally to have around.  You can outdamage him not problem, which means the mob will always stick to your dark butt while your pet is not even thought about, this is your key to victory.  If you position yourself that you are infront of the mob and your pet is directly behind him, he will hit much more often than usual.  We shadowknights don't get kick or dual wield...why? because we have a little guy back there making up for that damage we are missing.  All you have to do is put a semi-decent...I'm talking even tarnished or even rusty, weapon put him in back of the mob and we will do wonders for you. Cazic-forbid you put a fine steel two handed sword in his hands, you may have to even type in /pet no taunt if you do so.  However, don't summon your evil boney little friend in a dungeon unless you are going to stay put, I found this out the hard way =(.
<br><br>
Next is fear. FEAR! Fear has got to be one of the greatest spells we ever get, EVER!  It can be just as useful to us as it is to our robe-wearing friends, the necros, if you employ it correctly.  A necro usually dots the mob, uses darkness and fears it while letting his pet wack at it while it runs like a little girl, but if a shadowknight uses fear, we'll have our pet hitting it and we'll be nailing the mob everytime for practically max damage.  The difference between us and them is we like to get our hands dirty.  Look at your spell list next time your dueling a wizard and they think the fight is over because they rooted you, if you are wise they'll be in for a very rude awakening, into the next world...
<br><br>
Remeber also to use your lifetap line, people see it as crappy damage but I see it as reducign the damage I'm taking.  Suppose at 30th level, a mob hits me for 100 points of damage, I'll tap him for 40+ so in reality he only did less than 60 dmg to me which is alot more bearable, no? Combined with fear I'd love to find out that I actually gained hit points from a battle instead of being at one bub shouting to donate for a heal.
<br><br>
These are just generic tips that I've found out the hard way through adventuring.  I know many of my dark brothers and sisters will disagree with me on this but I think I've been rather successful following the advice I've given. I've also had a lot of fun this way.  I hope all young shadowknights who read this can learn from my mistakes and grow to be true warriors of darkness.<br><br></p>
		</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
